# Example test plan for lazy-http
#
# A real create → read → update → delete round-trip that actually persists,
# followed by an "echo" section that asserts on what the server received.
# No auth, keys, or setup required — just open it and hit "run from here" on the
# first step (or run any step on its own). It's designed to go green top-to-bottom.
#
# This file is also valid in the IntelliJ HTTP Client / VS Code REST Client.
#
#   api.restful-api.dev  a free CRUD store: POST returns an id we can then GET,
#                        PUT, PATCH and DELETE for real — so captured ids work.
#   httpbin.org          echoes the request back as JSON, so we can assert on the
#                        method, query string, headers and body the server saw.
#
# Tip: assertion values are compared literally — {{vars}} are expanded in URLs,
# headers and bodies, but NOT on the right-hand side of an @assert.
#
# Hosts and the token come from http-client.env.json, so pick an environment:
#   lazy-http --env dev example.http
# Only @gadget is defined inline below (it's request data, not environment).

@gadget = lazy-http tracker

### List all objects — also our reset anchor
### Marked with @reset: when it succeeds, lazy-http clears every other step's
### result and drops captured variables, returning the plan to a clean slate.
# @group Setup
# @reset
# @name Reset state
# @assert status == 200
GET {{api}}/objects
Accept: application/json

### Read a known sample object
# @group Smoke
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.id == 1
# @assert json.name contains Pixel
# @assert header.Content-Type contains json
GET {{api}}/objects/1
Accept: application/json

### Create a gadget
### Capture its id so every later step in this group can act on the same object.
# @group CRUD
# @name Create gadget
# @capture id = json.id
# @capture createdName = json.name
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.name == lazy-http tracker
# @assert json.data.inStock == true
# @assert json.data.year exists
POST {{api}}/objects
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "name": "{{gadget}}",
  "data": { "year": 2026, "price": 42.5, "inStock": true }
}

### Fetch the gadget we just created (uses the captured id)
### This is the round-trip that actually works: the object really exists now.
# @name Read it back
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.name == lazy-http tracker
# @assert json.data.year == 2026
# @assert json.id != 1
GET {{api}}/objects/{{id}}
Accept: application/json

### Replace it wholesale (PUT)
# @name Update gadget
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.name == lazy-http tracker v2
# @assert json.data.price == 39
PUT {{api}}/objects/{{id}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "name": "lazy-http tracker v2",
  "data": { "year": 2026, "price": 39.0 }
}

### Tweak a single field (PATCH)
# @name Patch name
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.name == lazy-http tracker v3
PATCH {{api}}/objects/{{id}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "name": "lazy-http tracker v3"
}

### Delete it
# @name Delete gadget
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.message contains deleted
DELETE {{api}}/objects/{{id}}

### Authenticated request — Bearer token in a header
### Shows {{token}} expanding inside a header value.
# @group Echo
# @name Bearer auth
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.authenticated == true
# @assert json.token == s3cr3t-demo-token
GET {{bin}}/bearer
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}
Accept: application/json

### Echo a POST and assert on what the server received
### httpbin reflects the method, query args, headers and parsed JSON body back.
# @name Echo round-trip
# @capture echoIp = json.origin
# @assert status == 200
# @assert json.method == POST
# @assert json.args.team == lazy
# @assert json.headers.X-Demo == lazy-http
# @assert json.json.ping == pong
POST {{bin}}/anything?team=lazy
Content-Type: application/json
X-Demo: lazy-http

{
  "ping": "pong"
}

### Print everything captured so far
### IntelliJ treats this block as a comment, so the file stays valid there.
# @group Utilities
# @shell
# @name Echo captured values
# @assert status == 0
echo "Created object id : {{id}}"
echo "Server named it   : {{createdName}}"
echo "Echo saw origin   : {{echoIp}}"
